9;t guarantee that you&#39;re going to get the best, but paying a 90% discount pretty much guarantees that you&#39;re in the bottom, let&#39;s call it half, I&#39;m being generous, probably quartile, that there&#39;s, you know, it&#39;s a market-based system. Don&#39;t you want the best people steering your $42 billion endowment? It&#39;s just so short-sighted.</p><p> Just goes to show you how important governance is. And since we&#39;re talking about governance, let&#39;s talk about another thing you had written that I was intrigued by. “What&#39;s in a name, the problem with ESG?” Now, we&#39;re not talking about wokeism or the political backlash, which is really a partisan political debate, what&#39;s the problem with ESG as a approach to value-based investing?</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. Well, let&#39;s start with the name itself. So ESG became a thing.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Environmental, social, and governance.</p><p> SEIDES: Three things which may or may not have anything to do with each other.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Clearly.</p><p> SEIDES: You can go back and say, “Remember FANG?” And then Fang had two A&#39;s, and then it turned into FANMAG. So these names have a way of taking off. Back in the day —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: BRIC, remember BRIC.</p><p> SEIDES: BRIC and emerging markets, Brazil, Russia, India, China. So the problem with ESG in its first iteration was that the label that everyone ascribed to it wasn&#39;t anything anyone could understand.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So let&#39;s track that evolution. This all started with divesting South African investments with, I think it was Harvard actually, or Yale was one of the Ivies that the student population wanted the endowment out of that, which led to socially responsible investing, which led to impact investing. Like there have been a ton of names. ESG just seems to be a catch all umbrella.</p><p> What should it be called or should it be called anything?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I think it goes back to what we talked about at the onset about beliefs. Each institution has to decide how do they want to align their investing with the purpose of the institution? What are they trying to solve for? So lots of people want to solve for, call it sustainable investing. What does that mean? I don&#39;t know. But the idea of an environment that humans can habit for centuries, seems like that resonates with people. So that leads to one set of sort of investment criteria that you could filter into your whole portfolio.</p><p> The S is really about diversity and that&#39;s important to a lot of people. Certainly in financial services, we recognize now that there are all these microaggressions that have been in place for decades. I&#39;m not sure how that turns into an investment strategy.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: See, I don&#39;t even think of it in those terms. I think of it as you want to avoid groupthink and if everybody went to the same undergrad, went to the same grad, went to the same training program, well, you&#39;re cranking out these automatons that are going to think, speak, and act similarly, and so the investment results will be similar, therefore subpar, so let&#39;s bring in different people from different backgrounds, different thought processes, different education, so that there is some robust diversity of thought.</p><p> I just don&#39;t, like the microaggression thing, I could care less about.</p><p> SEIDES: So the challenge is that the academic research shows that what you&#39;re trying to solve for is cognitive diversity.</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> SEIDES: Social diversity is a proxy for cognitive diversity.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Not a great one.</p><p> SEIDES: By the way, no, you could have people from all different races that think exactly the same way because they were educated at the same places.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: So the question is, if you care about improving your investment results from cognitive diversity, which we can all agree the research shows makes sense, is that a thing that you measure? Is that a thing that you evaluate? Like, how do you do that? So nobody really knows. And then governance, like, I&#39;m not sure I know of anyone, except for occasionally an activist investor as an opportunity set that is pro-poor governance.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Yeah, I can&#39;t really hear that anybody has been agitating for, “You need to make your governance worse.”</p><p> SEIDES: So what&#39;s evolved over the last couple of years is, starting with sort of Greta Thunberg, and then during COVID, when ESG took on this label, people created a whole bunch of products that nobody really understood what they were solving for. And so not that surprising, it hasn&#39;t really taken off in the way that a lot of people predicted four or five years ago.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But there&#39;s a ton of capital that has been allocated to, so let&#39;s work our way away from ESG. There are impact funds that go out of their way to make sure that half of their investments go to companies that are either managed by women or people of color, or are geographically away from New York, Boston, San Francisco, Silicon Valley, because the rest of the country has innovations and we&#39;ve been ignoring them.</p><p> And in fact, the competition in San Francisco and Silicon Valley is much more intense than Milwaukee or Orlando.</p><p> SEIDES: So I think that&#39;s right. The question is, what does a ton of capital mean? Right, in the scheme of things, The point I would make is that the amount of money that&#39;s gone into these different called diversifying strategies is much less than people thought it was going to be four or five years ago because it&#39;s all under this umbrella that each individual organization needs to figure out what do they care about and how do they want to deploy capital to meet that objective.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Don&#39;t some foundations have a sort of a checkbox approach? Hey, we want to give 5% of our alternative assets to funds run by women or funds run by minorities or LGBT, like down the list as a way of providing a little social diversity.</p><p> But again, the point you make is, is social diversity the same as cognitive diversity? Is it a good proxy?</p><p> SEIDES: They absolutely want to do that as long as those funds outperform.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s really interesting. So once the outperformance stops, we swap managers. That&#39;s really interesting.</p><p> Last question on ESG, certain folks have been saying, “Hey, you know, it works as a pretty good risk management filter. Boards that have 30, 40% women tend not to have the same sort of Me Too problems as a board that&#39;s all a whole bunch of old white guys. How do you respond to this is a risk management filter that allows us to identify the worst actors in corporate America?</p><p> SEIDES: I think that&#39;s a very reasonable way of looking at it. Again, depending on your investment strategy, are we talking about boards of stocks? What about in private markets? What about an early stage venture and a hedge fund? Like there&#39;s all different ways that you can think about integrating it and just like the problem with ESG, there&#39;s no one absolute solution that works for everything.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really quite fascinating.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk a little bit about capital allocators. What made you decide to play with this whole podcast thing?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I guess I was channeling my inner Barry Ritholtz some years ago. When I left Protege Partners, I wasn&#39;t sure what I would do, and I had picked up a bunch of, call it consulting or advisory relationships. And I had written that first book about hedge funds, which led me-</p><p> RITHOLTZ: In 2016, right?</p><p> SEIDES: In 2016.</p><p>里索尔兹：是的。</p><p> SEIDES: Which led me to be on a couple of podcasts. And I woke up one day and said, “Huh, maybe I&#39;ll run around and talk to my old friends.”我不知道。</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Dude, you&#39;re ruining my secret. It&#39;s the greatest gig, the easiest thing in the world, and now everybody&#39;s doing it. But for a while, it was my secret little garden that no one knew about.</p><p> SEIDES: And so I did that and I started a podcast called “Capital Allocators” and the idea was to be interviewing the people and make it be about the people, and then of course about investment strategies focused on the allocator CIO community and some of their favored money managers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And that&#39;s a rich, deep pool. People don&#39;t realize, you ever get the question, “Hey, are you worried you&#39;re going to run out of people?” I&#39;m like, “No, I got 10 million people to go. What, are you kidding me?”</p><p> SEIDES: There&#39;s never been a shortage of high quality people to have on. And so I started that six years ago, not knowing, certainly not thinking it would be a business. I used to joke, hey, Barry, we&#39;re going to have a conversation. Share it for free.” And just like the change bank from “Saturday Night Live, “We&#39;ll make it up in volume.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, right.</p><p> SEIDES: Like it was sort of a dot-com click business. And I just kept doing it for a number of years alongside of these other projects.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Which, by the way, something like 90% of the podcasts drop off within a year. They just, it&#39;s work, it&#39;s not easy.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, but it was just so much fun. And it was one of the things that —</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Again, you&#39;re ruining my secret. It&#39;s endless fun, right? I mean, think about, I went through the list of some of the people you spoke with. You could see there is delight in the conversation you have with people.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah. It&#39;s a version of what I did my whole career, right? I spent time interviewing money managers with a very, very different output mechanism. So in the past, I&#39;d have an interview with a manager and I would be evaluating them and I would mostly say no, but sometimes you&#39;d say, “Oh, what do I think of them?” And this is just, you have the same conversation. There&#39;s no evaluation. You get to be on everyone&#39;s team and then you share it with people. And what&#39;s happened over the years is it&#39;s become the largest podcast in institutional investing.</p><p> So that allocator community listens and people have incredible experiences when they come on. And it&#39;s just so rewarding. It&#39;s by far the most rewarding thing I&#39;ve done in my professional career.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I say to people, “This is the most fun I have all week.” And they look at me like, “Wait, what? You need to get a life.” I&#39;m like, “No, you don&#39;t understand.”</p><p>赛德斯：（笑）</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Is it the most fun you have each week when you speak to somebody?</p><p> SEIDES: Absolutely.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: But first of all, my dirty little secret, and I don&#39;t know if this is yours, I don&#39;t care who&#39;s listening. I invite people that I want to sit down with for an hour or two and have this conversation. If someone listens, great, but I don&#39;t care.是的。 It&#39;s like, “No, no, I have an audience of one.这就是我。 It&#39;s my selfish indulgence.” “Oh, okay, other people have listened.” But when you&#39;re picking people who invite, how much of it is, “Oh, I really want to sit down and talk to that guy or that girl.”</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s all of it. I still and always will source all the guests myself.</p><p> We do get a lot of inbounds and we figured out ways of getting more people involved that I might not have known about. But it is entirely, “Hey, what do I think is interesting? “Who would I like to talk to?” And you go from there.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: You focus primarily on the institutional side of things. How does that translate into who listens? Do you want a broader audience or do you like this somewhat narrow but incredibly deep and knowledgeable listenership?</p><p> What led you in that direction other than that&#39;s the world you came from?</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s mostly that and it goes to what you said, which is I love having these conversations and have never advertised on the podcast. I&#39;m sorry, I&#39;ve never advertised for the podcast other than a couple little experiments.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So do you promote the podcast? Other than going on other people&#39;s podcasts, how do you get to the point where people are listening other than the circle of institutional allocators?</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s been entirely organic. We&#39;ve done a few little experiments, promoting and advertising, none of it&#39;s worked. So I&#39;ve never really cared about it. It is kind of like what you said. I didn&#39;t think of it as a business when I started. I barely do now. And people have found it because it added value to their professional careers.</p><p> So most of that audience, I would say, as far as we can tell, a little less than half is the institutional allocator community. And that spans endowments, foundations. Where I came from, it spans sovereign wealth funds, pension funds, incredibly global. And that reach, which I&#39;m sure you know –</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It&#39;s hilarious.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s so much wider than I ever could have imagined existed.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Because the internet is totally global and I&#39;m sure you&#39;ve had this experience. I&#39;ve had guests say, I heard from a kid I went to camp with who now runs a fund in Hong Kong. I mean, but there&#39;s nothing local about a podcast. If it&#39;s on the internet, it&#39;s totally discoverable. I&#39;ve also had the same experience with half. If half are institutional allocators, who&#39;s the other half?</p><p> SEIDES: Most of it&#39;s money managers. So it&#39;s most of the people in the community.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: The people they&#39;re allocating to.</p><p> SEIDES: That&#39;s correct. And then there&#39;s this other, right? So you get notes from students, from friends who are outside. It&#39;s just entertainment.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: MBA professors, you hear from professors saying, “Hey, I love this interview. “I assigned this to the class.”</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, it&#39;s just fantastic.</p><p> So that&#39;s one of the fun things about it is you just, anyone can listen.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So curve ball question. What&#39;s your favorite podcast guest story that you can tell publicly? Because we all have great stories, some of which not really FCC approved.</p><p> SEIDES: There are one or two of those, but not that many. I think I would even go all the way back to my very first episode. So it was with Steve Galbraith, who we mentioned earlier with Jack Bogle. And it was just this idea, I knew Steve, I knew he had a great story, and I sat down and recorded it. And I couldn&#39;t find the recording on the recording device after we finished.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGH)</p><p> SEIDES: And it was so good, I just said, I can&#39;t wait to share this with people. And then I thought that that was the end of my podcast career after the first recording. And it took a good friend of mine, who&#39;s a technical whiz to figure out, which actually wasn&#39;t that hard, I just didn&#39;t know how to do it, to extract the conversation from the recording device.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I&#39;m going to share a similar story with you. So normally I&#39;m in the Bloomberg studios. I got an engineer, I got all the latest equipment. I have the easiest gig in podcast. I show up, I said, “Hey, print this out for me, off we go.” One about five years ago, I&#39;m planning a trip to Silicon Valley. I tee up two interviews in a day, Mark Andreessen of Andreessen Horowitz and Nobel Laureate Bill Sharpe. And by coincidence, I couldn&#39;t find a place to record the Bill Sharp interview, Andreessen said, “Oh, do it here. “You could use our podcast studios.” They were great. So I sit down with Bill, so I do Andreessen in the morning, right? In the afternoon is Bill Sharp, after lunch. I sit down, I have my device, which the engineer has taught me 47 times how to do, and I start the podcast with Bill Sharp, and maybe 90 seconds in, I notice I&#39;m not recording.</p><p> And I just have my stomach sinks. And I imagine spending an hour and a half with Bill Sharp and not having it record. So I&#39;m like, “Bill, I&#39;m not getting a good audio level. “Let&#39;s start this again.” So I hit it and now the red light&#39;s on, the view meter&#39;s going crazy, and I could see it&#39;s recording. I go, “Let&#39;s start over. “I think you were too soft.” And I just adjust it and we do the recording. And to me, that was the nightmare scenario of missing, God, Nobel Laureate, imagine that. So you found the Galbraith…</p><p> SEIDES: Found the recording, went out, and the rest is history.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So that&#39;s really interesting. So we only have you for so much time, and I appreciate you tolerating my nonsense.</p><p> Let&#39;s jump to my favorite questions that I ask all of my guests, some of which I think I&#39;m ready to retire. Probably the first one I&#39;m ready to retire, which is a post-lockdown question. I was asking people, hey, what are you streaming? What&#39;s keeping you entertained during lockdown?</p><p> Let&#39;s see if you have an answer to that. What have you been watching that&#39;s interesting?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, I&#39;m a Ted Lasso guy, and I&#39;ve watched the finale of the last season three times.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I thought that was unfairly slagged. It was really good.</p><p> SEIDES: It was really good. So in addition to that, I had on the show last year a guy named Brent Montgomery, and Brent&#39;s a TV producer. He created Pawn Stars and Duck Dynasty. His latest show is called The King of Collectibles.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: And it&#39;s Pawn Stars meets sports. The guy named Ken Golden, who&#39;s one of the largest sports collectibles dealers.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> SEIDES: And it is so, so good.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Do you get into the massive amount of counterfeit crap that&#39;s in that space at all? Because I would, of all the junk I buy, sports collectibles is the last thing in the world I would ever risk a penny on. I&#39;m convinced there&#39;s some kid in some sweatshop in a basement signing Michael Jordan&#39;s name over and over again.</p><p> SEIDES: Yeah, they do show how they go through the authentication process, at least with this one very high quality dealer.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, I mean, I&#39;m sure there are ways to authenticate it, but every time I look at something on eBay, I just kind of like look it and go, no way.</p><p> SEIDES: This has, you know, it has Mike Tyson on it, it has all these incredible athletes and entertainers that get involved with this guy. It&#39;s a fantastic show.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really, that sounds really, really interesting.</p><p> Let&#39;s talk about books. You&#39;ve written two of them. What are some of the favorite books that you&#39;ve read and what are you reading currently?</p><p> SEIDES: This year, the favorite book I&#39;ve read is “Unreasonable Hospitality.”</p><p> RITHOLTZ: I just got that book. Somebody recommended it. It looks fascinating.</p><p> SEIDES: It&#39;s by Will Guidara, who&#39;s one of the founders of Eleven Madison, Danny Meyer&#39;s partner, and really describes in excruciating, thoughtful detail what it takes to be a creative customer, a customer-focused organization. It&#39;s a phenomenal book.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: For a long time, Eleven Madison was just, you know, Michelin rated, everything else. It was spectacular.</p><p> SEIDES: So that&#39;s my favorite one this year. The one I&#39;ve been reading most recently, which has been a long project before I go to bed, and it&#39;s a 10-year-old book, is Bill Simmons&#39; “Book of Basketball.”</p><p> So Bill Simmons wrote a book that ranked the top 100 basketball players, as again, 10 years ago, of all time, using both stats and his incredible knowledge and judgment, and it is addictive and incredibly fun.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So spoiler, was it Jordan or LeBron? Who does he rank as number one?</p><p> SEIDES: I&#39;m only up to 25, which is Bill Walton.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So you don&#39;t know.</p><p> SEIDES: I don&#39;t know yet.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: And you know, 10 years ago, was Curry really on the list?</p><p> SEIDES: So early on in the book, he had this tiered system and he talked about the players that weren&#39;t yet on it. And Curry was mentioned as one he didn&#39;t think would get onto the list in a future edition.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Hilarious, right? And now he&#39;s probably top 10, right? Is that a fair statement?</p><p> Last two questions. What sort of advice would you give to a recent college graduate interested in a career in either alternative investments, allocation, anything finance related?</p><p> SEIDES: Well, the general advice I give, and I heard it phrased beautifully by a guy named Eric Resnick, who runs the largest private equity firm for travel and leisure, was recently on our show. He was told early on, combine your vocation with your avocation, which is just a thoughtful way of saying, do what you love.</p><p> I think that&#39;s general.</p><p> The problem with finance and alternative investments I would give advice that Howard Marks gives, which is if you want to have a great career in this space, start 30 years ago.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s great. I love Howard.</p><p> And our final question, what do you know about the world of investing today? You wish you knew 25, 30 years ago when you were first getting started.</p><p> SEIDES: I think the importance of people. We&#39;re talking about governance and decision-making and it was something that David Swensen taught me early on. But you have to go through people in difficult times, experiencing good and bad behavior in those times to really understand that ultimately active management is a people business.</p><p> And yes, you have to have all the investment discipline and all the rigor that goes into that, but they are human beings that are making decisions and that evaluating people as a frame for how you think about where you want to allocate your capital is probably the single most important thing you can do.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Really fascinating stuff, Ted. Thank you for being so generous with your time.</p><p> We have been speaking with Ted Seides. He is the founder of Capital Allocator and the author of “Capital Allocators, How the World&#39;s Elite Money Managers Lead and Invest” and the host of the “Capital Allocators” podcast.</p><p> If you enjoy this conversation, well, be sure and check out any of the previous 498 podcasts we&#39;ve done over the past eight years. You can find those at iTunes, Spotify, YouTube, wherever you find your favorite podcast. Sign up for my daily reading list at ritholtz.com. Follow me on what&#39;s left of Twitter @ritholz. Follow all of the Bloomberg family of podcasts on Twitter @podcast.</p><p> I would be remiss if I did not thank the crack team that that helps put these conversations together each week, Justin Milner is my audio engineer. Atika Valbrun is my project manager. Sean Russo is my head of research. Paris Wald is my producer. I&#39;m Barry Ritholtz. You&#39;ve been listening to “Masters in Business” on Bloomberg Radio.</p><p></p><p style="text-align: center;"> ~~~ </p><p></p><p><iframe style="width: 100%; max-width: 660px; overflow: hidden; background: transparent;" src="https://embed.podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/masters-in-business/id730188152" height="450" frameborder="0" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" data-mce-fragment="1"></iframe></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/transcript-ted-seides/">Transcript: Ted Seides</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ;
